==English==

===Etymology===
{{root|en|ine-pro|*deyḱ-}}
* First attested in 1541.
* From {{der|en|la|abdicātus||renounced}}, perfect passive participle of {{m|la|abdicō||renounce, reject, disclaim}}, formed from {{m|la|ab||away}} + {{m|la|dicō||proclaim, dedicate, declare}}, akin to {{m|la|dīcō||say}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|en|/ˈæb.dɪˌkeɪt/}}
* {{audio|en|En-us-abdicate.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|transitive|obsolete}} To [[disclaim]] and [[expel]] from the family, as a father his child; to [[disown]]; to [[disinherit]]. {{defdate|Attested from the mid 16<sup>th</sup> century until the early 19<sup>th</sup> century.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|reflexive|obsolete}} To formally separate oneself from or to divest oneself of. {{defdate|First attested from the mid 16<sup>th</sup> century until the late 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|obsolete}} To [[depose]]. {{defdate|Attested from the early 17<sup>th</sup> century until the late 18<sup>th</sup> century.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|obsolete}} To [[reject]]; to [[cast off]]; to discard. {{defdate|Attested from the mid 16<sup>th</sup> century until the late 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}
#* {{RQ:Joseph Hall Hard Measure}}
#*:betray and '''abdicate''' the due right both of ourselves and successors
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[surrender]], [[renounce]] or [[relinquish]], as sovereign power; to [[withdraw]] [[definitely]] from filling or [[exercising]], as a high office, station, dignity; to fail to fulfill responsibility for. {{defdate|First attested in the mid 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}
#: {{ux|en|to '''abdicate''' the throne, the crown, the [[papacy]]}}
#: ''Note:'' The word ''abdicate'' was held to mean, in the case of James II, to abandon without a formal surrender.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1776|author=Edward Gibbon|passage=The cross-bearers '''abdicated''' their service.|title=The History of the Decline and Fall of the Roman Empire}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author={{w|Edmund Burke}}|title=Reflections on the Revolution in France|year=1790|passage=He '''abdicates''' all right to be his own governor.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|title=History of England from the Fall of Wolsey to the Death of Elizabeth|author={{w|James Anthony Froude}}|year=1856|passage=The understanding '''abdicates''' its functions.}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To relinquish or renounce a throne, or other high office or dignity; to renounce [[sovereignty]]. {{defdate|First attested in the early 18<sup>th</sup> century.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author={{w|Edmund Burke}}|title=Reflections on the Revolution in France|year=1790|passage=Though a king may '''abdicate''' for his own person, he cannot '''abdicate''' for the monarchy.}}

